    "tmj_block_UtYCDW": {
      "type": "tmj-block",
      "blocks": {
        "rich_text_7Mewpm": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text": "<p>I've consistently seen that braces will typically flattens the 'curve of spee' a bit. Because the jaw is no longer supported in multiple positions.</p>"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_D4G9EG": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text": "<p>A mouthguard serves almost like a doorstop that prevents the jaw from closing and stretches the soft tissue that surround the jaw and the skull.</p>"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_ntGJxe": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text": "<p>This 'inflates' the skull which allows cranial bones and the jaw to revert back to healthier positions over time.</p>"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_C4jMHz": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text": "<p>I've observed that the teeth will also move during this process (upright, untwist).  And the arches often expand.</p>"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_FBPAdU": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "rich_text": "<p>And so over time the damage that was done by the braces is slowly reversed (in my experience).</p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "rich_text_7Mewpm",
        "rich_text_D4G9EG",
        "rich_text_ntGJxe",
        "rich_text_C4jMHz",
        "rich_text_FBPAdU"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "heading": "How a flat mouthguard works (in my view)?",
        "padding_top": "pt-8",
        "padding_bottom": "pb-12"
      }
    },
